thought.text:
Interesting! Looking at the compiled output, I can see that the snippet `child` is NOT wrapped in `async_body`. But the boundary fragment IS. Let me look more closely...

Actually wait, looking at the output, the `child` snippet is just `($$anchor) => { ... }` and it uses `$.template_effect`. The interesting thing is:

```js
$.template_effect(($0) => $.set_text(text, $0), undefined, [() => deferred.promise]);
```

The async values is `[() => deferred.promise]` (NOT `$.save(deferred.promise)`). And the parameter is `$0`.

Looking at `template_effect`:
```js
export function template_effect(fn, sync = [], async = []) {
    flatten(sync, async, (values) => {
        create_effect(RENDER_EFFECT, () => fn(...values.map(get)), true);
    });
}
```

And `flatten`:
```js
fn([...sync.map(d), ...async]);
```

So `fn` receives `[undefined_result, async_result]` = `[async_result]`. Then `fn(...[async_result].map(get))` = `fn(get(async_result))` = `fn(actual_value)`.

Wait, but `fn` is `($0) => $.set_text(text, $0)`. So `$0 = actual_value`. This works!

